combined <- clean_names(combined)

1.1.1 salary_estimate

The information contained in salary_estimate will be used to create four new columns:

  • min_salary: the minimum salary in the salary range. Missing will be set to “-1”. Numeric
  • max_salary: the maximum salary in the salary range. Missing will be set to “-1”. Numeric
  • basis: per annum or per hour. Missing will be set to “-1”. Factor
  • source: provided by Glassdoor or Employer. Missing will be set to “-1”. Factor
combined <- combined %>% 
  mutate(min_salary = as.numeric(ifelse(salary_estimate == -1, -1, str_extract(salary_estimate, "(?<=^\\$)\\d{1,3}"))),
         max_salary = as.numeric(ifelse(salary_estimate == -1, -1, str_extract(salary_estimate, "(?<=-\\$)\\d{1,3}"))),
         salary_basis = as.factor(case_when
                                  (str_detect(salary_estimate, "Hour") ~ "hourly",
                                    salary_estimate == -1 ~ "-1",
                                    TRUE ~ "annual")),
         salary_source = as.factor(case_when
                                   (str_detect(salary_estimate, "Employer") ~ "Employer",
                                     salary_estimate == -1 ~ "-1",
                                     TRUE ~ "Glassdoor")),
         .after = salary_estimate) %>%
  
  # multiply the min_salary and max_salary by 1,000 if the salary_basis is annual
  mutate(min_salary = ifelse(salary_basis == "annual", min_salary * 1000, min_salary),
         max_salary = ifelse(salary_basis == "annual", max_salary * 1000, max_salary))

Check the salary ranges are valid and reasonable for each of annually and hourly

combined %>% filter(salary_estimate != "-1") %>% 
  group_by(salary_basis) %>% 
  summarise(min_salary_minimum = min(min_salary),
            min_salary_maximum = max(min_salary),
            max_salary_minimum = min(max_salary),
            max_salary_maximum = max(max_salary)) %>% 
  kable(col.names = c("basis", "minimum min_salary", "maximum min_salary", "minimum max_salary", "maximum max_salary"),
        format.args = list(big.mark = ',')) %>% 
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover"))

Figure 1.1: Annual salary range per role. Data Scientists have the largest range

1.1 shows that Data Scientists have the largest range and furthest extremes regarding the annual salary by possessing the lowest possible salary at $12,000 and the highest possible salary at $254,000. While business and data analysts possess a similar lowest salary at $27,000 and $24,000, respectively, business analysts have a higher possible salary at $226,000 compared to $190,000 that can be earned by data analysts. In addition, data scientists have a higher median salary at $101,000 versus $73,000 and $67,000 earned by business and data analysts, respectively. Furthermore, while the salaries for business and data analysts are concentrated towards the lower part of the range, the salary range for data scientists is more evenly distributed

shinyApp(
ui <- fluidPage(

server <- function(input, output, session) {
  aflw_numeric <- aflw_scags[,3:15]
  output$parcoords <- renderPlotly({
    dims <- Map(function(x, y) {
      list(values = x, range = c(0,1), label = y)
    }, aflw_numeric, names(aflw_numeric), USE.NAMES = FALSE)
    plot_ly(type = 'parcoords', dimensions = dims,
            source = "pcoords") %>%
      layout(margin = list(r = 30)) %>%
      event_register("plotly_restyle")
  })

  ranges <- reactiveValues()
  observeEvent(event_data("plotly_restyle", source = "pcoords"),
               {
                 d <- event_data("plotly_restyle", source = "pcoords")
                 # what is the relevant dimension (i.e. variable)?
                 dimension <- as.numeric(stringr::str_extract(names(d[[1]]),
                                                              "[0-9]+"))
                 # If the restyle isn't related to a dimension, exit early.
                 if (!length(dimension)) return()
                 # careful of the indexing in JS (0) versus R (1)!
                 dimension_name <- names(aflw_numeric)[[dimension + 1]]
                 # a given dimension can have multiple selected ranges
                 # these will come in as 3D arrays, but a list of vectors
                 # is nicer to work with
                 info <- d[[1]][[1]]
                 ranges[[dimension_name]] <- if (length(dim(info)) == 3) {
                   lapply(seq_len(dim(info)[2]), function(i) info[,i,])
                 } else {
                   list(as.numeric(info))
                 }
               })
  ## filter to the rows that match the selection ranges
  aflw_selected <- reactive({
    keep <- TRUE
    for (i in names(ranges)) {
      range_ <- ranges[[i]]
      keep_var <- FALSE
      for (j in seq_along(range_)) {
        rng <- range_[[j]]
        keep_var <- keep_var | dplyr::between(aflw_scags[[i]],
                                              min(rng), max(rng))
      }
      keep <- keep & keep_var
    }
    aflw_scags[keep, ]
  })
  output$data <- renderPrint({
    tibble::as_tibble(aflw_selected())
  })
},

options = list(height = 600)
)

4.1 a.

The tests to be conducted below will assess if there is a significant difference between the margarine brands in the mean of the cholesterol reduction after four weeks, as such a new variable measuring the cholesterol reduction after four weeks will be created, and will be the basis of the forthcoming analysis.

# create 4 week difference variable
chol <- chol %>% 
  mutate(red_4weeks = Before - After4weeks)

The two-sample t-test is conducted:

with(chol,
     t.test(red_4weeks[Margarine == "A"],
            red_4weeks[Margarine == "B"]))
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  red_4weeks[Margarine == "A"] and red_4weeks[Margarine == "B"]
## t = -2.5186, df = 15.934, p-value = 0.02285
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.2967641 -0.0254581
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
## 0.4855556 0.6466667

The Wilcoxon rank sum test is conducted:

with(chol,
     wilcox.test(red_4weeks[Margarine == "A"],
                 red_4weeks[Margarine == "B"]))
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  red_4weeks[Margarine == "A"] and red_4weeks[Margarine == "B"]
## W = 16, p-value = 0.03388
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0
a_mean <- round(mean((chol %>% filter(Margarine == "A"))$red_4weeks), 2)
b_mean <- round(mean((chol %>% filter(Margarine == "B"))$red_4weeks), 2)

ggplot(chol, aes(Margarine, red_4weeks)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  geom_hline(yintercept = a_mean, color = "red", linetype = "dashed") +
  geom_hline(yintercept = b_mean, color = "blue", linetype = "dashed") +
  theme_minimal() +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = c(a_mean, b_mean)) +
  theme(panel.grid = element_blank()) +
  labs(y = "Four Weeks Reduction",
       title = "Cholestrol Reduction After Four Weeks per Brand Boxplot") +
  annotate("segment", x = 1.5, xend = 1.5, y = .5, yend = .64, colour = "#EC7014", size = 1,
           arrow = arrow(ends = "last")) +
  annotate("text", x = 1.65, y = .53, label = "33%", size = 10)

Figure 4.1: Four week reduction in cholesterol per brand. Brand B achieved one-third greater reduction than A 

ggplot(chol, aes(red_4weeks, color = Margarine)) +
  geom_density() +
  geom_vline(xintercept = a_mean, color = "red", linetype = "dashed") +
  geom_vline(xintercept = b_mean, color = "blue", linetype = "dashed") +
  theme_minimal() +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(.2, .4, a_mean, b_mean, .8)) +
  labs(y = "",
       x = "Four Weeks Reduction",

  theme(axis.text.y = element_blank(),
        panel.grid = element_blank()) +
  annotate("segment", x = .5, xend = .64, y = 0, yend = 0, colour = "#EC7014", size = 1,

Figure 4.2: Four week reduction in cholesterol per brand. Brand B achieved one-third greater reduction than A

The p-values of both the two-sample t-test and the Wilcoxon rank sum test are both under 0.05, leading to the rejection of the null hypothesis that the means in the reduction of both brands are not significantly different. This is further supported by figures 4.1 and 4.2 which show that Margarine B achieved an approximately 33% greater reduction in cholesetrol on average than Margarine A. The figures also show that Margarine B has more observations with a greater reduction than the average reduction in cholesterol than Margarine A. It can therefore be concluded that the mean differences are significantly different between the two Margarines, and Margarine B is superior with regards to cholesterol reduction.
